    "In the linear plot, it is difficult to see the tail of the distribution, where the power-law behavior would be most evident. This happens because there are few cells with very high counts of incidents, which makes the low number of thefts dominate and make it hard to see the distribution of the majority of cells with high counts. This is counteracted in the loglog plot, where the axes are scaled logarithmically. This will also be used to answer if the theft/larceny follows a power-law distribution by looking at the log-log plot. If the points in the loglog plot form a straight line, that would indicate a power-law distribution. In this case, the points do not form a perfect straight line, but they do show a clear downward trend, which suggests that the distribution of theft/larceny incidents across cells follows a heavy-tailed distribution, which is consistent with a power-law distribution.\n",
    "\n",
    "The average block becomes a misleading statistic in this case, because it does not capture the high concentration of theft/larceny in a small number of cells. If theft/larceny is highly concentrated in a few hotspots, then the average block will be skewed by those hotspots and will not represent the typical experience of most blocks in the city. This meaning that on average or on paper, a block might have a certain number of theft/larcenys, but in reality, most blocks will have very few theft/larcenys. It could possibly be more informative to look at the median to get a better sense of the typical block."
